segments.text: Today is Thursday, April the 17th, 1997.
We're at your home in Austin.
Would you please tell me a little bit about your upbringing, where you were raised, and all this kind of thing?
I was raised in Junction City, Kansas.
Were you?
Yes.
My dad was from Tecumseh, Kansas.
I and my five children immigrated to Austin in 1965.
In 65?
Okay.
And how old were the children when you got here?
Oh, ranging.
Well, now they're, I can tell you what they are now.
They range from 40.
Seven to forty-three now.
And so you couldn't take it back to sixty-five and figure out how old I was.
Anyway, it was ridiculous for Frankie and I to marry with nine kids.
I want to hear about that.
When you came to Austin, did you start working with the press right away, or what did you do?
You never worked at Press, okay.
I worked at the UT campus with the police corps program.
Oh, okay, all right.
I have a master's degree in linguistics.
Okay.
And then I worked at, uh, Houston, at, uh, Houston Tourism.
Okay, yeah.
Uh, how'd you happen to meet Frank Woodlawn?
I met him at a, a Houston-Hilson University of Texas party.
why they got together, sociology department of all things.
And he just stopped in.
He was walking at night, every night, and he would stop in at various friends' houses for coffee.
And I've met him now.
And you had five children, and Frank had four children.
And you decided you really need...
I think they made a television show about me.
I think so.
Didn't they?
Now, tell me, if I might inquire further, was your husband, former husband, first husband, living?
Yes.
I was divorced at the time.
How about Frank?
His wife had just died.
When did she die?
I was trying to remember if it was 69 or 68.
I cannot remember.
Okay, and he had four sons?
No, two sons and two daughters.
Two sons and two daughters.
I never really checked that out.
I'm not saying too much about it.
And you had four, five children, and they were sons and daughters?
Yeah, four sons and a daughter.
Four sons and a daughter.
That was the business.
And did you, when you married, did you all really live under the same roof for a while?
Yeah.
They were, well, two of my boys went to Cal College, both friends.
Okay, yeah.
And my daughter just went to high school, I think, she's forty-seven now.
They were pretty well-qualified.
Yeah.
And when you married, you lived where?
We lived up at the Edenroth Apartments first.
And then we bought a duplex, and we lived in a duplex, and then we bought a little home out.
So, and that was what year again, 16?
We were married January 1st, 1970.
January 1st, 1970.
And Frank?
No.
Frank was 15 and a half years older than I.
Okay.
He was born in 1913.
Yes.
When you walked into that world, publishing in the University of Texas Press, how did you feel about it?
I mean, what did you see there?
In the first place, I thought that Frank, when I met him, had something to do with newspapers.
Okay.
I can understand that in the way he talks, probably.
And so I didn't know anything about the University Press, or any of the University Presses.
But I soon found out.
I bet.
And was impressed.
Was it fun?
Oh, it was fun.
That's a key word of our time at A.M. was fun.
Yeah, I see that a lot in his correspondence.
When you were here now at Texas from 1970 to 1974, you all, I assume now, were pretty closely entangled, let's say, with the Betacheks and Nobby and that sort of thing.
He was.
He was.
They had all died before.
They had already been.
OK.
I didn't believe you then.
I'm glad you told me.
Mm-hmm.
But the widow, I remember we went to an autograph party for the widows once at Schultz Garden.
Yeah, I remember Mrs. Dudley, and I remember him vaguely, just... Walter Webb was another one.
Walter Prescott Webb, yes.
And we loved his wife.
So that world had pretty well already gone.
Yes.
When you walked into the situation.
Except for Frank.
Yeah, sure.
Who retained the spirit of...

did how did frank feel about texas from 70 to 74 to the press and austin and the university he got pretty fed up with john silver okay i knew john silver john silver's son was in my fraternity i believe jack and i met him he was dean okay i'm just nostalgic
I don't know how John Silver is, but they had attempted to pack the board with Erebus, and it was such one struggle.
That's right.
And I know Frank just kind of defined the faculty here, he said at the time, as disgruntled.
Now, Spur was the president for a while.
Yes, he was.
I think when a bank retired.
We went and set up a house for a farewell or something like that.
Now, you all went to... Help me reconstruct how it was that you happened to get to Texas A&M.
John Lindsey.
Okay.
Now, when did you remember first encountering John Lindsey?
The first year or two, we were married.
Okay, you were early on.
Yes.
Now, I don't remember when Frank knew me.
Okay, what I'm kind of leading, you can help me.
What I kind of get out of all this, and talking to Lindsay too, is that John didn't know Frank Wardlaw until, but he knew Buck Shewitz real well.
Yes.
And Buck asked John Lindsay to come
to a party, I'm going to say, at Austin.
And I should be able to tell you what party that was, but I've already forgotten.
And Lindsey met Frank.
And they hit, and this was Lindsey's expression, they hit it off, right away.
And Frank also needed John Lindsey at that moment.
because he wanted Buck to do another book.
Oh, I see.
Okay.
Does that sound reasonable?
It does sound reasonable.
Okay.
It does.
And he thought John could help him get Buck to do that book.
Buck always had to be persuaded.
I know that.
So that was Buck, but apparently then things really...

worked out and everybody seemed to have a good time for a while, and y'all were frequent visitors, let's say, I don't know how frequent, but anyway, you visited John both in Houston and Galveston at that beach house.
Yes.
Now, let me get to a critical moment.
This is from Lindsay's account, and also from Frank's comments in that
Catch-22, Style-22, that article anyway.
He kind of explained how it was happening there, but there's a little difference in the version.
And I really believe John Leeson's is probably the right one, because Frank was writing, I think, public, all consumption.
But anyway, John said, and I'm doing most of the talking, so just stop me whenever you're ready.
John said that you and Frank were in his house,
And not in Houston.
Frank was fussing about the faculty.
And his advisory committee and all things were kind of going to pieces.
And so John's version is that he said, well, Frank, basically, why don't you quit bitching and come to Texas A&M?
I did not overhear this conversation, but it sounds true.
He says you did.
He says you were there.
And he says, then the next response was,
And he may not have put it in quite those immodest words, I don't know.
Anyway, he said, come and where you'll be appreciated.
And Frank said much the same as Frank said in his article that you all were at the beach house and so forth.
And Frank said that his response was, well, this is a terrible time to start a press.
And John Lindsay's comment was that both of you stopped and looked at him and didn't say one word.
I don't remember that.
Okay.
I kind of believe the Lindsay version.
Because, well, it's hard to believe, I guess, that Frank didn't have a response, I guess, to something at the moment.
But anyway, I think it startled everybody, from what I kind of gathered.
I don't think Frank had ever thought about it.
Never thought of it.
I really don't think so.
No, I don't think, everything I can figure.
In fact, for a man over 62.
Yeah.
do this was very unusual.
Yeah.
He was thinking retirement.
That surprised me all through his letters, and I'm sure you wrote.
He was planning what he was going to do when he retired.
And what was going to happen to the press after he retired.
And he was going to retire in 1965, whatever year it was.
He had it.
plan, and he did it.
I was amazed.
When the time came when he was 65, he wasn't quite ready, but his doctor, Dr. Lipscomb, and I, we were ready.
I like Harry Lipscomb.
I haven't seen him in years, but he and I got friendly for a while.
He's nice.
Oh, he's a lovely man.
But anyway, then, according to Lindsay, in the version I'm developing,
you two didn't really respond.
Now, in Frank's article, he says, when I explained that, you know, we couldn't come because it was a terrible time to start a quest.
Well, that's true.
But anyway, then John says, and I think this is probably correct, that Frank called him about two or three days later after he had left Houston.
He probably had another run in the silver.
And said, John,
I'm going to talk to you about coming to A&M.
And John Lindsay said, and I think he's right, I'm way ahead of you.
Because what John Lindsay had already done, I have this pretty well documented.
Set up an interview with Jack Williams.
Yes.
He had it cold.
I remember that.
He had gone to the board of directors.
He had three board members who were all ready for this.
In fact, they were Clyde Wells and all this.

guy in waco his name is me anyway three boys and and he told called uh jack williams and said i'm i'm asking frank wardlaw to come to a m and start a press what do you think about it i was wondering if there was much commotion about a press if that's all right well that's see that's what i've been working on i don't think much i think it was kind of a

foggy notion maybe because and one thing that was going on I do know this I was already writing that Centennial History thing and I had started that in 1969 and it was just about done in fact it was finished by 72 73 and then of course Rutter had died and we had a lot of confusion because Jack Williams became president in 73 I believe it was he'd just come in
Frank was flounder of Jack Williams and almost any administrator living or dead.
I want to ask you about that too.
But then Lindsey had all this put together so he and Jack came to talk to you and Frank.
Is that right?
I think we had a luncheon outside the home.
In fact, Frank told him to meet him at the Vagabond Motel, because he didn't want to be seen so badly.
That's what it was.
That sounds like Ring the Bell.
And Lindsay, I'm still laughing about that.
So anyway, so that was the next step.
Jack Williams and Lindsay talked to Frank.
Now, what year was this?
That was 17... No, that was 17...
still 74.
I think that was the spring, maybe it was either late 73 or the spring of 74.
I believe it was the spring of 74.
I remember Frank coming home from that meeting saying, Jack Williams is a fine fellow.
That was the first time they met.
Okay, that's what I had too.
Another question I'm trying to figure out is, where did the real initiative for this press come from?
Was it Jack Williams, or was it John Lindsay, or who?
I think a combination.
I think so too.
But I still don't know how it came to pass.
No, I don't think they do either.
And in fact, that's what I kind of gathered from talking with Lindsay.
He said, well, Frank, why don't you come over here and we'll start a press.
It never had occurred to him before.
And then he was tickled.
Yeah, and then I said, well, John, do you like books and so forth?
No, I don't care for books.
So I was trying to figure out, but what he cared for, of course, was A&M.
He's the biggest Aggie in the world.
He'd do anything for A&M.
And this seemed to be good for A&M.
And I thought, well, maybe this guy really liked books or art or whatever.
He did like Frank, and he did like Zach Williams, and that little mix worked nicely.
So, then you and Frank go to Austin, to, I'm sorry, to College Station.
Yes.
When was it, in August?
That's about right.
No, no, not the move.
You moved in August, but you went over there to see the signs.
Weren't too terribly thrilled.
Okay, that's what I wanted to know.
No.
When did this happen that you decided to come to college?
I don't know, but I knew for months and had to keep quiet about it.
Well, I'm making a story out of this, and I'm not sure it's right, so you might knock it in the head real quick if it isn't right.
But John Lindsay again said, well, we were driving around, and I went to the old board of directors' house.
Pick up Buck.
Pick up Buck.
Okay, good.
That's what I'm looking for, a confirmation.
And he said, while I went in to get Buck, you and Frank got out of the car and walked around the house.
And he thinks, I think, that was the moment you decided to come to College Station.
I just wonder.
Well, we had no idea what... College Station isn't the most beautiful place in the world.
No, not in 1916, not in 1972 or what it was.
Well, the campus itself was fine.
Yeah.
We loved living there.
Still hear those...
Those boys yelling back and forth, bad words at each other.
That's another world.
But to live on the campus.
That's really changed.
The old Aggies are fading, I think.
For better or for worse.
But I kind of thought that that might really be the time when y'all decided this was okay.
Did you have any sense of that at all?
No, we didn't know for sure for quite a while.
Okay.
It still makes a good story.
Yeah, I think it was Frank's idea.
Wouldn't this be a one-population plant?
And it was.
Because I can't even visualize the new one.
I mean, it's too fancy.
Who else has offices where everybody has a bathroom?
A tub.
Yeah, ten bedrooms.
That's right.
Well, all the other rooms, not the apartment.
Each one had a bathtub.
It was a bathtub.
A great big bathtub.
Which didn't do Buck much good.
He couldn't get in and out of it.
I think he had a shower put in on top.
Now, so you decide to come.
How'd you feel about that, leaving Austin?
Did you have any sense?
Anything he wanted.
I did not care.
I mean, about leaving Austin, I had only been here a few years, so I don't have any roots here.
Now, and when you got to College Station, and you moved into the old Board of Directors' house,
Can you kind of just describe things that really hit you?
It was just marvelous, but it was dingy.
Okay, yeah.

And nobody mentioned anything about rehab in the place, and we wanted it so badly for what it was that mostly I spent my time making grapes and this and that, spreading out the furniture so it didn't look too bare.
Did you bring your own furniture?
Did they?
Okay.
Except for the sheets.
Yeah, okay.
Old-fashioned cacao sheets.
Starched.
Oh, luxury.
I think I remember that Aggie Laundry.
I can't exactly remember.
It was real close.
Now what about
Did you have any sense of Texas A&M, like the kids?
Oh yes, immediately.
We had two dogs at the time, two Scotties, and we would go out every night and walk the dogs, and everybody would say howdy to us.
Yeah.
And that was nice.
In fact, Frank had been coming in some of his letters.
Did the military flavor bother you particularly at the time?
No.
Was that Vietnam time?
I can't remember.
Yeah, that was.
And there wasn't much stirring around Aggieland over that.
No, that's right.
And just when Ohio and Austin, too, were getting the permit,
Very conservative.
And still is, but it's changed.
Our kids, well of course we, I have a son who went to Vietnam, and Hank's son.
You entertained a lot in the press.
Yes.
We had three bedrooms.
spare bedrooms.
And I don't think a week went by without an accident.
No authors or just people.
And oh, after the football games, we were the only place on the campus that dispensed free booze, and were we popular.
And you enjoyed it?
Frank enjoyed it?
Oh yes, we loved it.
I was busy too, just being a hostess.
Yeah, I'm sure you were.
That's a big part of the whole...
I remember John Graves said, this is the only place I like to stay overnight.
Well, usually I stay at a hotel when I go someplace, but this place is fun.
It was fun, you know.
Everybody had that sense, and that's what kept, I think, everything so upbeat.
And compared, apparently, to what... And of course, the staff was just crackerjack.
Oh, they were always friendly.
It was small.
It was for a long time.
It was just Gayla.
Yeah, Gayla and Margaret.
And Don Collins comes in a little later.
And then Noel didn't come in until 75 or 76, but there were three to start with.
Oh, Ray Gamayi.
Oh, yes.
Right.
That's who it was.
Those three.
That was the start of it.
And Ray didn't really get there until February, I think, of 75.
I can't remember how.
Frank courted Ray.
Early on, and he brought him down almost the same time y'all moved in.
August through September.
Ray came down and visited the campus.
And there's a letter there.
And in fact, then I saw the bill for the entertainment that he sent for his reimbursement to Buckwires.
And they've taken Ray out to barbecue twice.
somewhere else, I forget where, and then at your house, you know, several times, and he was there about a week, he and his wife.
Is she still there?
No, I don't think so, I don't know.
I've never heard anything of her.
I'll ask Gayla.
Gayla really keeps in touch.
I didn't know that.
And Gayla's still there.
She was a person.
I was with Frank when he interviewed her.
Is that right?
I thought, oh my God, she's so young.
Frank said, one look at her.
That's it.
His choice of people.
Who is outstanding.
That's incredible.
You know, that's amazing for that press, that the people who come and stay.
That's what makes it go through.
That's very impressive.
So those three, and then Don Collins comes in.
And he's a wonderful guy, and he was.
And Don is still around somewhere.
Chicago.
OK.
It was the last I heard.
Yeah, I probably should call him and talk to him in the phone or something.
And then Noel came in about, what, 70, maybe even 77.
I haven't really talked to him, but somewhere around there.
But it was a small staff.
Small staff?
And I think he did four things this year?
Four or six, I can't remember.
Have you seen Elizabeth's job?
Yes.
No, I'm going.
As soon as I leave here, I'm going to go see her.
Yeah, she was quite close, being the first book, you know.
Yeah, right, yeah.
And I knew her.
I had met her, and I liked the book.
Yeah.
It's a good book.
So I'm anxious to visit with her.
Now, Frank, you and Frank both, did you feel like that was a 24-hour interview?
How did you feel about the work?
It was a whole life.
Just a lifestyle.
A lifestyle that was so rare and wonderful.
To any man who loves his work as much as Craig does his, it's just a wonderful thing to behold.
Yeah.
And I think that's the impression coming up with everybody that he encountered.
And then when you can have a book in your hand to show for you, it's a wonderful thing.
And it's pretty.
He loved books.
And Frank was so interested in everything.
I still remember him telling me that he didn't like this.
He was a hot lead man.
Yeah, it's good he passed before.
And in fact, that A&M history, that Centennial history I did,
was printed at Taylor Printing Company.
Oh, really?
On their computers.
And I, he, Frank, and Buckwires, and I went up there to tour the plant.
I remember that.
Yeah.
And Frank was down there doing that computer stuff, you know.
That's not real printing.
Which I thought was fun and interesting.
Were there any...
big problems or encounters that you remember?
I cannot remember any.
I honestly can't.
You block them out, okay.
He needed his head tatted a little bit, you know, and he got it.
He was the emperor of all, Mr. Ray.
And he enjoyed it after being snubbed and
snarled at here for so many years.
That's what I get from Lindsey and Williams and Buck Wires.
Now, Buck, did you know Buck Wires?
Well, Buck had a bad stroke about four years ago.
Oh, he's died.
And he's done a lot of recovery and recuperation.
And he said, frankly, Henry said, I have forgotten almost everything.
But, he said, I do remember this.
He said, if Frank wanted something, we've got it for him.
Yes.
And I think that's wrong.
Complete respect and admiration.
And after the deal went through here at UT, it was just fun.
Well, that's good.
That's a nice way to do it.
Incidentally, I had a friend in South Carolina, University of South Carolina.
I called him the other day because I needed the name of the guy who hired Frank.
McKissick.
That's South Carolina.
McKissick.
Was it McKissick?
Okay, well, he told me Admiral Smith or something like that.
Oh, maybe.
That was in 1945.
Now, McKissick was a professor of journalism, I believe.
Okay, that would be right, too.
Anyway, he wheeled and wheeled because Frank had, what, three semesters of college?
Yes, yeah.
And wow, suddenly it moved.
Maybe 8,000 years.
Speaking of that, there's a good comment.
I can't remember if it was Webb.
Maybe Webb.
When Frank came to...
Texas, I believe it was, when Frank recounted or something.
Yeah, he said he didn't have any degrees, but he'd work on them in his spare time.
Yes, and Webb said, don't bother.
He said, what we don't need is somebody with a degree over here.
And he went through a long ritual about, well, if you get a
You know, the bachelor's degree, you don't have much.
You have to get a master's.
If you get a master's degree, then you have to go with a Ph.D. And if you get a Ph.D., it hasn't educated you at all.
So you don't need that.
Which I thought was neat.
I've used that in the book.
Frank always would feel that maybe he should have.
He couldn't be.
His daddy was a Presbyterian minister during the Depression.
Mom, now, yeah.
Frank was.
Well, he was in the WPA.
Yeah.
And I think that salary was... CCC.
CCC.
And I think that was either $16 or $27 a month.
I forget what it was.
Mm-hmm.
Which she sent home.
One or the other.
And half at least went home.
Maybe all of it.
That's right.
So I can't imagine.
But it's good that he, in my mind, it's good that he didn't get that degree because that would have cast him in another mode.
Well, he had no trouble dogging on with AP.
Now, any high points that you especially remember about your time at?
Buck lived with us, and he was so wonderful.
It was during his dry period, and he was very, very super sensitive.
Like he would know when we wanted to be alone, and he would drift off.
But he would eat his meals, and he was so fun.
And they had been good friends before.
Well, Frank had published his book here.
But that was a bad time for Buck and I.
And Frank was trying to help Buck.
Yeah.
And he really worked on it to get that book out of again.
Oh, yeah.
I remember a little of that.
I remember that.
We had quite a few books that read through the last of them.
And when he came, he knew this was going to stay on.
